Description:
[vouwblad] Karen Mensel (June 1969), Preference for 24 calendar pictures, sometimes even 36, suggests that the miniaturists (around 1500) were interested in elaborating on the tradition of calendar iconography. A few independent spirits- the more accomplished painters - occasionally break with the more traditional iconography. All calendar pictures, not just the full page illustrations to be taken into consideration. Instances of differing motifs for the same month. [schema: scan: recto-verso];
Ad [Addendum] Months:
J. BOUISSOUNOUSE, Jeux et travaux d'après un livre d'heures du XVe siècle, [(Documents artistiques du XVè siècle; 3)], Paris [Droz], 1925;
J. [James] FOWLER, On Medieval Representations of the Months & Seasons, Archaeologia, XLIV, 1873, [pp.] 137-224;
LE SÉNÉCHAL, J. [Julien], Les occupations des mois dans l'iconographie du Moyen Âge, Bulletin de la Société des Antiquaires de Normandie, Caen-Rouen, Paris [tôme 34], 1924;
TUSSER, T. [Thomas], Five Hundred Points of Good Husbandry, [At London: Printed for the Company of Stationers, an. Dom.], 1614;
WEBSTER, J.C. [James Carson], The Labors of the Months in Antique and Mediaeval Art & The End of the 12th C., [(Northwestern University Studies in the Humanities; 4)], Evanston, Ill. [(Princeton Monographs in Art and Archaeology; 21), Princeton: Princeton University Press], 1938;
WILLARD, James F., Occupations of the Months in Mediaeval Calendars, Bodleian Library Quarterly Record, vol. VII, [1932], N° 74, pp. 33-34 [=33-39];
SCHAPIRO, M. [Meyer], Review of Webster, in Speculum XVI, 1941, [pp.] 131-137.
